= The Coservatorio Congress

On  June  11th the delegates of the CNT convened extraordinarily to resolve the big issues dividing the union. The congress is split in two sides, with some exceptions, following the split along the lines of reformist unionists and anarchists.
On one hand, there are the delegates around Angel Pestana (reformists) and Joan Peiro (unionists), who are, more or less, friendly of the Republic, for fear of the rightist reaction. The leading faces among these delegates are, like Sr. Peiro, members of the National Committee and the anarcho-syndicalist Solidaridad group. Sr. Pestana himself is the Chairman of the Committee. The editorial committee of the union's main newspaper in Barcelona, Solidaridad Obrera, is also full of their sympathisers
On the other hand are the militant FAIstas and especially the people around the Nosotros group, as well of the anarchist intellectuals, like Diego Abad de Santillan (on some issues). Being inspired by the struggles of their exile revolutionaries, these delegates are more radical in their demands and their actions. They oppose any tollerance of the state and support revolutionary actions. They are still a loud minority, but are fastly gaining popularity among the union members with in their rhetoric.

One of the most provocative points on the agenda list of the Congress is proposed by the National Committee and it concerns the position of the CNT about the Constituent Cortes and the policies discussed by its participants. Before the proposal a review of some recent acts of collaboration done by the Committee sparked outrage among some of the 511 delegates at the Congress, though indeed it is known (especially in Catalonia) that there have been instances of support between the anti-dictatorial forces during the Primo de River regime. 
The National Committee supports the need of discussion on this topic since the Republican Cortes was the result of many "revloutionary acts" in which the CNT played a big part. On the other hand, the anarchists pointed out the contradiction of having such deliberations with the anti-authoritarian principles laid out at the union's founding congress and our stance against any support or recognition for the State authority, republican or monarchist.

Many delegates don't seem to notice the contradiction in these these two positions or stand on the fence. Joan Peiro defended in his speech the need for gradual methods, essentially postponing the revolution and supporting a limited form of support for the more radical propositions and their advocates in the Constituent Cortes, even though he finished his speech with an assurance of his anti-parliamentarism.
What is the will of the unions?

